AGI - In the night sky above the port of Mikuriya in the city of Daisen, nine mysterious pillars of light appeared in Japan.&nbsp; Since May 20, the social media platforms X and Line&nbsp (the most used social in Japan) have been invaded by images depicting 9 pillars of enigmatic light that cross the sky over the Asian country. This phenomenon tagged with the hashtag "#ninepillars", has triggered a wide speculation, ranging from extraterrestrial activity to other supernatural theories.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2> What do we know about these mysterious pillars of light and their possible origin?> &nbsp;</h2>
"It is interesting to note that many fans of the anime "Neon Genesis Evangelion", a famous Japanese series that explores themes of catastrophe and rebirth, have associated the pillars of light with the "Third", a crucial event in the narrative of the series," says Renato Reggiani, journalist and researcher who for years lives and works in Seoul. "In "Evangelion", the Third Impact is an apocalyptic event characterized by intense visual and spiritual manifestations, a reference that many fans have found visually similar to the light pillars observed."
&nbsp;
The images first appeared on X (previously Twitter) in a user post @theinformant_x, quickly obtaining attention and generating theories about their origin. Spiega Reggiani: "A similar post appeared on Instagram on the user's page @sutalworld, describing the phenomenon of the "9 pillars of light" visible in the night sky over a Japanese coastal city, finally also the prestigious magazine Newsweek was interested in the phenomenon with its fact checking column that confirmed the originality of the photos but hypothesized a much less imaginative origin of the phenomenon. After a deeper investigation, it seems that these pillars of light are not mysterious as initially thought. The pillars of light are a well documented optical phenomenon caused by light reflection from tiny ice crystals suspended in the atmosphere. Light sources can be natural, such as the sun or the moon, or artificial, like lampposts.”
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Weather experts confirm that the conditions in the night in question were favourable to the formation of light pillars. Cold weather, serene sky and calm wind allow ice crystals to form in the air near the ground, acting as reflectors for light from various sources. Still the Italian researcher: “The local residents and officers noticed that on the night when the images were taken, there were several sporting events and festive decorations involving significant artificial lighting. These conditions have probably contributed to the visibility and intensity of the light pillars observed. The light pillars observed above Japan were not the result of extraterrestrial activity or supernatural phenomena. Instead, they were spectacular manifestations of a natural atmospheric condition amplified by human activity in the area.”
&nbsp;
Shared photos online may have captured the imagination of many around the world, but the explanation is firmly rooted on Earth and judging by the image above&nbsp; in which the sea is seen, it would seem like the reflections of the lamps used by Japanese fishermen for octopus fishing.
